---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Galaxy Bimodality - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Galaxy Bimodality</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Galaxy Bimodality</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Observational phenomenon</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Discovered:</th>
                    <td>~2000s (formalized)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Key Papers:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Strateva_2001" text="Strateva et al. (2001)" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Baldry_2004" text="Baldry et al. (2004)" /></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Red_Sequence" text="Red Sequence" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Blue_Cloud" text="Blue Cloud" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Green_Valley" text="Green Valley" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Galaxy bimodality</strong> refers to the observed division of galaxies into two distinct populations based on their properties, most notably their colors and <WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation_Rate" text="star formation rates" /><sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>. This fundamental feature of the galaxy population manifests in multiple parameter spaces, including the <WikiLink slug="pages/Color-Magnitude_Diagram" text="color-magnitude diagram" />, where galaxies separate into the <WikiLink slug="pages/Blue_Cloud" text="blue cloud" /> and <WikiLink slug="pages/Red_Sequence" text="red sequence" /><sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup>.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Observational Evidence</h2>
        
        <p>The bimodality is most clearly seen in optical color distributions, where galaxies show two distinct peaks:</p>
        
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Blue galaxies</strong> (typically g-r &lt; 0.6): Actively star-forming, disk-dominated systems with ongoing gas accretion</li>
            <li><strong>Red galaxies</strong> (typically g-r > 0.8): Quiescent, often <WikiLink slug="pages/Early-Type_Galaxy" text="early-type galaxies" /> with little ongoing star formation</li>
        </ul>

        <p>The separation becomes more pronounced at higher stellar masses, leading to the concept of <WikiLink slug="pages/Mass_Quenching" text="mass quenching" />. The <WikiLink slug="pages/Green_Valley" text="green valley" /> represents the sparsely populated transition region between these populations.</p>

        <h2 id="section-1">Physical Drivers</h2>

        <p>Multiple mechanisms have been proposed to explain the bimodality:</p>

        <h3>Internal Processes</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Morphological_Quenching" text="Morphological quenching" /> - The buildup of a <WikiLink slug="pages/Classical_Bulges" text="stellar bulge" /> stabilizes gas disks<sup>[2]</sup></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/AGN_Feedback" text="AGN feedback" /> - Active galactic nuclei heat or expel gas</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Stellar_Feedback" text="Stellar feedback" /> - Supernovae and stellar winds regulate star formation</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Bar_Formation" text="Bar-driven evolution" /> - Bars can drive gas inflows and trigger central starbursts</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Environmental Effects</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/environmental_quenching" text="Environmental quenching" /> - Suppression of star formation due to the cluster/group environment, whose effectiveness depends on <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall time" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Ram_Pressure_Stripping" text="Ram pressure stripping" /> - Removal of gas in dense environments</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Strangulation" text="Strangulation" /> - Cutting off the supply of fresh gas</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Harassment" text="Galaxy harassment" /> - Repeated high-speed encounters</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/preprocessing" text="Preprocessing" /> - Environmental effects at large cluster-centric radii, before virial radius crossing</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Evolution and Transitions</h2>

        <p>Galaxies are thought to transition from the blue cloud to the red sequence through <WikiLink slug="pages/Quenching" text="quenching" /> processes. The timescale and nature of this transition remains debated:</p>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Evidence for Rapid Quenching</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>The sparsely populated <WikiLink slug="pages/Green_Valley" text="green valley" /> suggests fast transitions</li>
                <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Post-Starburst_Galaxies" text="Post-starburst galaxies" /> show evidence of recent, rapid shutdown</li>
                <li>Some <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Simulations" text="simulations" /> require fast quenching to match observations</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="evidence-against">
            <h4>Evidence for Slow Quenching</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Many red galaxies show extended <WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation_History" text="star formation histories" /></li>
                <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Morphological_Transformation" text="Morphological transformation" /> appears gradual</li>
                <li>Environmental quenching mechanisms operate on Gyr timescales</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-3">Redshift Evolution</h2>

        <p>The bimodality evolves with cosmic time. At higher redshifts:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The red sequence was less populated at z > 1</li>
            <li>The transition mass between populations decreases with time</li>
            <li>The color separation was less pronounced in the early universe</li>
        </ul>

        <p>See also: <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Evolution" text="Galaxy Evolution" />, <WikiLink slug="pages/Downsizing" text="Downsizing" /></p>

        <h2 id="section-4">Open Questions</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>What is the primary driver of bimodality - mass, morphology, or environment?</li>
            <li>How do galaxies maintain their position in either population?</li>
            <li>What determines quenching efficiency and timescales?</li>
            <li>Can galaxies rejuvenate and return to the blue cloud?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-update-2603-13010">Updates from arXiv:2603.13010</h2>
        <p><WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" /> provide new tools for quantifying how <WikiLink slug="pages/environmental_quenching" text="environmental quenching" /> drives bimodality. Their continuous calibration of <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="galaxy infall time" /> (T<sub>inf</sub>) from <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase space" /> position enables observers to estimate how long a satellite has been exposed to environmental processes<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>. Key implications for bimodality:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>The T<sub>inf</sub> distribution is often bimodal (early vs. late infallers), suggesting that even at a fixed location in a cluster, satellite populations have mixed environmental exposure histories<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>Environmental quenching timescales can now be inferred continuously as a function of redshift (0 &lt; z &lt; 1), rather than relying on discrete zone assignments<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>.</li>
            <li>Host halo mass does not significantly affect the infall-time calibration, suggesting universal environmental processing once local phase-space position is accounted for<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>.</li>
        </ul>

